                <h1>Understanding Background Extinction Rate: Nature's Norm</h1>
                <p>The background extinction rate refers to the normal rate at which species go extinct over time due to natural processes, typically estimated at about 1 to 5 species per million species per year. It serves as a baseline to measure the current rate of extinction, which is significantly higher due to human activities.</p>
